{Women defeat men horribly in thirty historical games. Jan van Reek. Amalie
Paulsen (1831-1869) was not allowed to participate in tournaments. This game
is played at the estimate of her family.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 3... f5 $6 {
The original Philidor Defence.} 4. dxe5 fxe4 5. Ng5 5... d5 {Philidor considere
d the conquest of the centre as won for Black. White's counterattack is known
from Atwood-Bruehl, London 1796.} 6. e6 $1 6... Nh6 {
Tis position was fashionable in 1858, due to a consultation game of Morphy.} 7.
f3 {Wielfried plays a recommendation by the Bilguer.} (7. Nc3 c6 8. Ngxe4 dxe4
9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qe5 Rg8 11. Bxh6 Bxh6 12. Rd1 {(Atwood-Wilson, London 1798)}
12... Qg5 $5 {(Staunton & Owen-Morphy & Barnes, London 1958).}) 7... Bc5 $5 8.
fxe4 O-O 9. exd5 Rf5 10. Nc3 Bb4 11. Bc4 {
Amalie has sacrificed the centre pawns and continues with her razor-sharp play.
} 11... Qf6 $5 (11... Re5+ 12. Kf1 Rxg5 13. Bxg5 Qxg5) 12. Nge4 $6 (12. Qd2 $1
12... Ng4 13. Be2 $1 {consolidates.}) 12... Qh4+ 13. Ng3 Re5+ 14. Be2 14... Nf5
{Four Black pieces are placed between the lines and attack on the king.} 15.
Rf1 $2 (15. Qd3 c6 16. Bd2 {protects the weaknesses.}) 15... Nxg3 16. Rf4 $6
16... Nxe2+ $1 17. Rxh4 Nxc3+ 18. Kf1 Nxd1 19. Rxb4 19... Bxe6 $6 (19... Rxd5 {
wins simply.}) 20. dxe6 Rxe6 21. Rd4 Ne3+ 22. Bxe3 Rxe3 23. Rd8+ Kf7 24. Rad1
$6 ({Rellstab advises} 24. Re1 {
After the text Black is able to develop the Queen's side at last.}) 24... Re8
25. R1d3 Nc6 26. R8d7+ 26... Re7 {
Amalie's tactical wit precedes Judit Polgar's play.} 0-1

